:"1240","1185":"1185","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","1216":"1216","1201":"1201","bef 18-MAR-1229":"18. marts 1229","1200":"1200","about 1216":"omkring 1216","1265":"1265","1229":"1229","Iden, Rye, Sussex, England":"Iden, Sussex, England, United Kingdom","Radnor, Wales":"Radnorshire, Wales","of Iden and Isham, Sussex":"Iden, Sussex, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"about 1170–bef 18-MAR-1229":"circa 1170–18 maart 1229","1170–1229":"1170–1229","1170–Female":"1170–Overleden","1185–1240":"1185–1240","1216–1265":"1216–1265","1164–1200":"1164–1200","1160–1201":"1160–1201","about 1170":"circa 1170","1164":"1164","1240":"1240","1185":"1185","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","1216":"1216","1201":"1201","bef 18-MAR-1229":"18 maart 1229","1200":"1200","about 1216":"circa 1216","1265":"1265","1229":"1229","Iden, Rye, Sussex, England":"Iden, Sussex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Radnor, Wales":"Radnorshire, Wales","of Iden and Isham, Sussex":"Iden, Sussex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1170–bef 18-MAR-1229":"about 1170–18 March 1229","1170–1229":"1170–1229","1170–Female":"1170–Deceased","1185–1240":"1185–1240","1216–1265":"1216–1265","1164–1200":"1164–1200","1160–1201":"1160–1201","about 1170":"about 1170","1164":"1164","1240":"1240","1185":"1185","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","1216":"1216","1201":"1201","bef 18-MAR-1229":"18 March 1229","1200":"1200","about 1216":"about 1216","1265":"1265","1229":"1229","Iden, Rye, Sussex, England":"Iden, Sussex, England, United Kingdom","Radnor, Wales":"Radnorshire, Wales","of Iden and Isham, Sussex":"Iden, Sussex, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Auberville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Turberville  . This form of the surname is very rare in Britain and Ireland."],"variants":[{"name":"Turberville","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name, probably from Thouberville (Eure), or possibly from Trubleville (Seine-Maritime), both in France. The two may have been confused in surname usage."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert d' Auberville was born about 1170, in Iden, Sussex, England, United Kingdom, his father, William de Auberville II, was 8 and his mother, Mathilda de Glanville, was 11. He died on 18 March 1229, in his hometown, at the age of 60."},"et":{"about 1170–bef 18-MAR-1229":"umbes 1170–18. märts 1229","1170–1229":"1170–1229","1170–Female":"1170–Surnud","1185–1240":"1185–1240","1216–1265":"1216–1265","1164–1200":"1164–1200","1160–1201":"1160–1201","about 1170":"umbes 1170","1164":"1164","1240":"1240","1185":"1185","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","1216":"1216","1201":"1201","bef 18-MAR-1229":"18. märts 1229","1200":"1200","about 1216":"umbes 1216","1265":"1265","1229":"1229","Iden, Rye, Sussex, England":"Iden, Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Radnor, Wales":"Radnorshire, Wales","of Iden and Isham, Sussex":"Iden, Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 11